    <div class="col-lg-9">
      <h1 class="display-5 mb-4">Better Together</h1>

      <p class="lead">Better Together is the design philosophy behind Community Engine: communities deserve tools that strengthen trust, participation, stewardship, and local autonomy instead of extracting attention or locking people into someone else's platform logic.</p>

      <div class="alert alert-secondary" role="alert">
        <strong>Seed content note.</strong> This page is intended as starter content for new Community Engine platforms. Operators are encouraged to adapt it so it reflects their own history, values, and community purpose.
      </div>

      <h2 class="h4 mt-5">What Better Together Means</h2>
      <p>Community Engine starts from the assumption that healthy communities need more than publishing tools. They need shared spaces for trust-building, mutual aid, governance, invitations, discovery, collaboration, and accountability. Better Together names that intention directly: people and communities flourish through connection, shared responsibility, and accessible participation.</p>

      <h2 class="h4 mt-4">What the Platform Tries to Protect</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Human-scale participation instead of engagement extraction.</li>
        <li>Clear privacy boundaries instead of silent behavioral profiling.</li>
        <li>Host control and self-determination instead of platform dependence.</li>
        <li>Shared stewardship instead of purely top-down administration.</li>
        <li>Accessible, reusable building blocks instead of brittle one-off custom code.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="h4 mt-4">How This Shows Up in Community Engine</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Invitation-aware onboarding that helps communities grow intentionally.</li>
        <li>Role-based access and privacy-aware publishing controls.</li>
        <li>Built-in community, event, exchange, and content systems that can be combined instead of rebuilt.</li>
        <li>Internal metrics focused on what happened, not on identity tracking by default.</li>
        <li>Operator-extensible policies, docs, and pages that can be adapted without losing the original scaffolding.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="h4 mt-4">A Toolkit, Not a Walled Garden</h2>
      <p>Community Engine is meant to be reused, taught from, and adapted. The open-source repository should remain a source of truth for the platform's design philosophy, architecture, history, values, and lessons learned. The built-in pages, policies, and agreements are part of that toolkit: they are not filler copy, but reusable starting points that should help new platforms onboard faster and with fewer blind spots.</p>

      <h2 class="h4 mt-4">What New Platforms Should Do Next</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Review and adapt the built-in policies, agreements, and public pages for your community and legal context.</li>
        <li>Document your own operator contacts, hosting details, subprocessors, and moderation process.</li>
        <li>Keep the values and governance story visible, not hidden in code or private docs.</li>
        <li>Treat the starter content as an onboarding scaffold you improve, not generic text you ignore.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
